|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/international/21579039-chinas-growing-empire-ports-abroad-mainly-about-trade-not-aggression-new-masters The new masters and commanders]
|passage=From the ground, Colombo’s port does not look like much. . . . For mariners leaving the port after lonely nights on the '''high seas''', the delights of the B52 Night Club and Stallion Pub lie a stumble away.}}

====Usage notes====
* Usually used in the plural form, although examples of the singular form can be found, as in:
::* {{circa|1830}} [[w:James Fenimore Cooper|James Fenimore Cooper]], ''The Water Witch'', ch. 16:
::*: "[T]he commander of this vessel must get a passport of Her Majesty's cruiser, ere she again enter the '''high sea'''."
* Often used in the phrase ''on the high seas''.

